Honestly, when i was exploring which path to take, I was drawn to mobile 
because everyone everyone around was literally living on the phones that's
where the real day to day interaction with real technology happens.
I found that idea more exciting than building something that mostly lives in
a browser tab.

Then when I looked deeper into mobile develpment specifically. Flutter stood out
for a very practical reason - One codebase, two platforms. As Someone starting out
I didn't went split my learning effort into "Swift for iOS, Kotlin for Android".
Flutter let me learn the dart once and actually ship to both platforms, Which felt
like a smarter use of time and effort especially early in my carrer.

Beyond that, I liked how fast the feedback loop is in Flutter — the hot reload feature 
meant I could tweak a UI and see the result instantly. which made learning fun instead of 
frustrating And when I actually started building — first in my personal project Tijori+, 
then during my internship at VKAPS — I realized I enjoyed the UI/UX side of things a lot.
Getting a screen to look and feel exactly right, working closely with designers in Figma, 
debugging why a widget isn't rendering the way I expect — that whole process just clicked 
with me.

It's not that I looked down on web development — it just never grabbed me the way building 
something you can hold in your hand and show your family did. And once I got into real
production work — like the grocery delivery app I maintain now at Foduu — dealing with
real users, real bugs, real performance issues, it confirmed that mobile was the right 
choice for me.

So in short: mobile because it's where people actually live, and Flutter because it let me move
fast and build for both platforms without doubling my workload.
